The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Bihar BDO in vigilance trap
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Bihar BDO in vigilance trap
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Patna, May 15: The vigilance department today arrested a block development officer, a teacher and a clerk for accepting bribe in separate incidents.         
	Mohammed Tanveerul Quamar, the BDO of Shivajinagar, Samastipur, was arrested for accepting Rs 50,000 from Tapeshwar Singh, the headman of Shankarpur panchayat, before sanctioning 54 Indira Awas and crop damage insurance claims for several villagers.        
	The additional director-general of police (vigilance) Neelmani told The Telegraph: The BDO had demanded Rs 1 lakh and had received Rs 10,000 from the headman as the first instalment. We recovered Rs 55,000 cash from the BDO.         
	The additional director-general also added that his team had laid a trap to nab the official red-handed.         
	In another case, Nawal Singh, the assistant principal of a government primary school at Jehangirpur (Motipur) in Muzaffarpur, was arrested while accepting Rs 7,200 from one Sanju Kumari, a teacher, for marking her present on the days she was away from the government school.        
	Purnendu Choudhary, a clerk at the district provident fund office at Samastipur, was also arrested while accepting Rs 3,200 from one Ravindra Kumar for expediting the processing of retirement benefits of his mother, who retired as a government teacher recently.        
	The additional director-general of police (vigilance) added: Since 2006, we have managed to arrest 221 public servants, including 75 gazetted officers.         
	Our most prominent arrests were of the former Madhepura district magistrate, H.C. Jha, of two civil surgeons and some divisional forest officers.                                                                                                                                                                         
